        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To achieve the goals proposed above, we want to map the HCN(1?0)
emission along the northern part of the bar, up to a radius of 80?. To
do this, we need to observe with a mosaic of three adjacent fields of
70? (beam size at 88 GHz) overlapping at the center of the bar. this
will cover a distance of 2.2 kpc transversal to the main axis of the
bar, reaching the fainter star forming regions down streaming the bar.

These observations are proposed with the C34-1 configuration (4.22?
resolution) which is better than the BIMA-SONG observations (~6?) and
sufficient to compare precisely with the star forming regions (H?
emission). At the distance of NGC 2903, the spatial resolution will be
of 180 pc.

From our IRAM-30m observations, we can expect a line intensity of 10-60
mJy/beam with a velocity resolution of 20 km/s. The correlator is set up
to cover ~470 MHz which is enough at 88 GHz to observe the complete
velocity range of the HCN(1?0) line in NGC 2903.

We are expecting variations of the HCN(1-0) emission on a scale of
5-10?, which is adequately compatible with configuration C34-1. In any
case, we could also use our IRAM-30m data to recover the short-spacings
emission.

We have added one continuum spw to our spectral setup, because it comes
for free, but we are not expecting to see any continuum emission at band 3.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
